In the context of Jobs-to-be-Done (JTBD), a push and a pull refer to different approaches to driving customer adoption and usage of a product or service.
A push occurs when a company actively reaches out to potential customers to promote their product and encourage its adoption. This could involve marketing campaigns, sales efforts, or other proactive measures to get the product in front of customers who may not be actively seeking it out. The company is essentially "pushing" the product onto the customer.

To create an LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor with Arduino, you can follow these steps:

1. Connect the LM35 temperature sensor to your Arduino board. The sensor's VCC and GND pins should be connected to the Arduino's power and ground, respectively. The analog output pin of the LM35 should be connected to the analog input pin A0 of the Arduino [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

2. Connect the LCD to the Arduino. If you are using an I2C LCD, you will need to install the LiquidCrystal_I2C library by Frank de Brabander in your Arduino IDE. Go to Tools > Manage Libraries, search for "LiquidCrystal I2C," and install the library [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].

3. Connect a 10K Ohm potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel. The first pin of the potentiometer should be connected to +VCC, the second pin to pin 3 of the LCD, and the third pin to GND [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

4. Upload the code to your Arduino board. You can find sample code and detailed explanations in the tutorials mentioned in the references [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd), [2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd), [3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)]. The error message is telling you that the `using enum` feature requires C++20 or later. By default, Visual Studio uses an older version of the C++ standard.

To enable C++20 in Visual Studio 2022, you can follow these steps:

1. Right-click on your project in the Solution Explorer.
2. Select "Properties" from the context menu.
3. In the Properties window, go to "Configuration Properties" > "General".
4. Look for the "C++ Language Standard" option.
5. Change the value to "ISO C++20 Standard (/std:c++20)".
6. Click "Apply" and then "OK" to save the changes
